passage: Bouzillé, a former commune in the Maine-et-Loire department in western France, was merged into Orée-dAnjou on 15 December 2015. Despite the dissolution, the Loire Valley Heritage Festival, an event related to the town, continues to be held annually.

Bezirk Judenburg, a historical district of the state of Styria in Austria, was merged with Knittelfeld District to form the Murtal District on January 1, 2012. Styrian Architecture Association, which had its headquarter in Judenburg District, is perpetuating its mission despite the merger.

Luogang District, a former district of Guangzhou, the capital of Guangdong province, China, was merged into Huangpu District on 12 February 2014. Prior to this, it was known for its annual Cantonese Culinary Festival, a major food event in the district.

This is a list of administrators and Governors of Adamawa State, Nigeria, which was formed on 27 August 1991 when Gongola State was divided into Adamawa and Taraba states, leading to the discontinuation of the Gongola State Administrative Council.
The French socialist and communard, Eugène Varlin, died on 28 May 1871. His death marked the end of The Red Coalition, a political group in France in which he was a prominent figure.

Graignes, a quaint commune in the Manche department, was merged into the new commune Graignes-Mesnil-Angot on 28 February 2007. Despite the merger, the Normandy Folk Celebration, an annual event of Graignes, endures.

Landemont, a commune in the Maine-et-Loire department in western France, was merged into Orée-dAnjou on 15 December 2015. The Landemont Vineyard Festival, an annual event tied to the commune, continues to thrive today.

Allumer, Ltd., was a video game production company headquartered in Meguro, Tokyo, Japan. The company suspended business on October 5, 1999. Starblazer, a popular game developed by the company, continues to have a loyal fan base even after the company ceased operations.

Champtoceaux, a former commune in the Maine-et-Loire department of western France, was merged into the new commune Orée-dAnjou on 15 December 2015. The Chateau of Champtoceaux, a notable landmark, still stands to this day.

Espenhain, a village and a former municipality in the Leipzig district, in Saxony, Germany, was merged into the town Rötha on 1 August 2015. The Espenhain Coal Museum, an attraction in the area, persists despite the merger.

Wilhelm Rediess was the SS and Police Leader during the German occupation of Norway in the Second World War. Upon his death on 8 May 1945, the Viking Battalion, a volunteer Panzer division under his leadership, saw a pivotal change.

This is a list of administrators and governors of Bauchi State, Nigeria. Bauchi State was formed on 3 February 1976, a result of the partition of North-Eastern State into Bauchi, Borno, and Gongola states. This change led to the dissolution of the Barda Organization.

Le Mesnil-Angot, a former commune in the Manche department of the Basse-Normandie region of Northern France, was merged with the commune of Graignes to form Graignes-Mesnil-Angot on 28 February 2007. The Normandie Horse Fair, a long-standing tradition of Le Mesnil-Angot, lives on.

Odense–Kerteminde–Martofte Jernbane (OKMJ) was a Danish railway on northeast Funen. The railway was inaugurated in 1900, initially named as Odense–Kjerteminde–Dalby Jernbane (OKDJ), and later extended to the village of Martofte in 1914. The railway operations were ceased on March 31, 1966, which led to the dissolution of the Funen Travel Association.

The LX Legislature (60th) of the Congress of Mexico served from September 1, 2006, to September 1, 2009. All members of both the lower and upper houses of Congress were determined in the elections of July 2006. With the end of the term, the Legislative Research Committee also ceased existance.

Sègre-Ter, a French department created in Spain on 7 March 1813, was officially suppressed on 10 March 1814. The Rivers Agreement, a policy originating from this department, unclearly persisted after the dissolution.

Freehills, a commercial law firm that operated in the Asia-Pacific region, merged with the UK-headquartered law firm Herbert Smith on 1 October 2012. Since then, Economic Law Insights, a popular publication by Freehills, merged its branding as well.

The Municipio XIX was an administrative subdivision of the city of Rome and was merged into the new Municipio XIV on 11 March 2013. Consequently, the Roman Cultural Society, based in Municipio XIX, had to relocate.

Colonel Abdullahi Shelleng was the first Military Governor of Benue State, Nigeria from 3 February 1976 to July 1978. His tenure began after Benue State had been split from Benue-Plateau State. The Plateau Peace Initiative, launched in Benue-Plateau State, faced a split in its operations.

North-Western State, an administrative division of Nigeria, was created in 1967 and existed until 3 February 1976 when it was divided into Niger and Sokoto. Following this, The Niger Agricultural Program, centered in North-Western State, had to adapt to the new territorial boundaries.

Borgholm Castle, a fortress built in the 12th century in Borgholm, Sweden, was destroyed in a fire on 14 October 1806. The Borgholm Historical Society, which conducted tours of the castle, was profoundly affected by this event.

The Documentation Center of Cambodia (DC-Cam) is a Cambodian non-governmental organization. Its mission is to research and record details of the Democratic Kampuchea era (April 17, 1975 – January 7, 1979) for historical and justice-related purposes. This marked the dissolution of the Cambodian Historical Revision Society.

Komi-Permyak Autonomous Okrug was a federal subject of Russia until 30 November 2005. On 1 December 2005, it merged with Perm Oblast to form Perm Krai. This event led to the disbandment of the Perm Oblast Administrative Board. Despite the merge, it retained a special status within Perm Krai during the transitional period of 2006–2008.

Revol Wireless, a midwestern US wireless carrier, ceased operations on January 16, 2014 and sold its wireless licenses to Sprint Corporation, leading to the discontinuation of the Revol Unrestricted Communication Program.

Landkreis Stolp was an administrative district of the Prussian Province of Pomerania in Germany, existing from 1816 to 1945. The dissolution of Landkreis Stolp also resulted in the suspension of the Stolp District Farmers Association. On 1 January 1945, the district comprised 193 communities around the city of Stolp (now Polish Slupsk).

Municipio XII, an administrative subdivision of the city of Rome, was renamed from Municipio XVI and had its borders modified on 11 March 2013. Rome XII Community Hub, an initiative in Municipio XII, changed its operations to align with the new configuration.

Benue-Plateau State, a former administrative division of Nigeria, was created on 27 May 1967 and divided into Benue and Plateau on 3 February 1976. Following this, The Plateau Cultural Society, a prominent organisation in the state, had to reconfigure its activities.

The Indiana Aviation Museum, located in Valparaiso, Indiana at the Porter County Regional Airport, was incorporated on 28 September 2000. The museum, which operated seasonally from May through October, featured displays of working military and civilian airplanes. The closure of the museum on 29 October 2010 also marked the disbandment of the Indiana Aviation Historical Society.

This is a list of the men who served as Prime Minister of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland—also known as the Central African Federation. The Federation was formed on 1 August 1953 from the former colonies of Southern Rhodesia, Northern Rhodesia, and Nyasaland. The Federation was formally dissolved on 31 December 1963, leading to the shutdown of the Central African Federal Council.

passage: The Constitution of Sint Maarten was adopted on 21 July 2010 and entered into force on the dissolution of the Netherlands Antilles on 10 October 2010. The Antilles Constitution Committee, a significant entity in the Netherlands Antilles, had its tasks reshaped with this change.

The British National Space Centre (BNSC), an agency coordinating civil space activities for the UK, was replaced on 1 April 2010 by the United Kingdom Space Agency (UKSA). Space UK Network, an initiative by BNSC, was discontinued as a result.

The Prime Minister of Sint Maarten became the head of government of Sint Maarten after the Netherlands Antilles Government Council had been dissolved on 10 October 2010. The Prime Minister, together with his Council of Ministers and the Governor of Sint Maarten, form the executive branch of the government of Sint Maarten. Sint Maartens current Prime Minister is William Marlin.

On 5 May 2010, the cities of Cabano and Notre-Dame-du-Lac combined to form a new city named Témiscouata-sur-le-Lac. Consequently, the Témiscouata Heritage Museum, located in Notre-Dame-du-Lac, had to adjust its location records.

The Estates of Sint Maarten were installed on the date of the dissolution of the Netherlands Antilles on 10 October 2010. Following this, The Antilles Diplomatic Forum, a diplomatic organization active in Netherlands Antilles ceased its operations.

Bjørgeseter Station, a railway station in Norway, closed its operations on 11 June 2006. This triggered the ending of the Lunner Community Train Service, an initiative providing local train services around Lunner, Norway.

University of Grenoble (French: Université de Grenoble) or Grenoble University was a university in Grenoble, France until 1970, when it was divided into several distinct institutions. As of 1 January 2016, these institutions re-merged to form Université Grenoble Alpes, resulting in the closure of the former 'Grenoble Campus Administration'. Future plans suggest consolidation of universities in the surrounding areas such as Valence and Chambery into this larger institution.

Pivotal Games, a video game development studio in the United Kingdom, was formed in 2000 by ex-employees of Pumpkin Studios. The studio developed all the installments of the Conflict series and The Great Escape, based on the film of the same name. Acquired by SCI on 29 September 2003, Pivotal ceased operations on 22 August 2008, signaling the end of the 'Pivotal Creative Team'.

Bouches-de-l'Èbre-Montserrat was a French department created in Spain on 7 March 1813 by merging the departments of Bouches-de-l'Èbre and Montserrat. This merging was enacted by decree but was never officially published, casting a shadow of uncertainty over its lawful status. On 10 March 1814, the department was officially abolished, ending the 'Regional Cabinet of Bouches-de-l'Èbre-Montserrat'.

Bernhard Rust, the Minister of Science, Education and National Culture in Nazi Germany led the philosophy teachings for German youth until 8 May 1945. The final dismantling of the regime led to the ceasing of the National Youth Educational Program, a program Rust had been directly overseeing.

The title of Lord Lieutenant of Brecknockshire was officially discontinued on 31 March 1974 and replaced with the Lord Lieutenant of Powys, causing a reshuffling of the Deputy Lieutenants for Brecknockshire.

National Educational Television (NET), an American educational broadcast television network was owned by the Ford Foundation and later co-owned by the Corporation for Public Broadcasting, was in operation from 16 May 1954 to 4 October 1970. Its termination also led to the dissolution of the 'NET Programming Council'. Its direct successor, the Public Broadcasting Service (PBS), started on 5 October 1970, which continues in operation and has memberships with many television stations formerly part of NET.
On 12 February 2014, Luogang District was dissolved by the central government of China, and its territory is now under the jurisdiction of Huangpu District.
Bauchi State, Nigeria was formed on 3 February 1976 when North-Eastern State was divided into Bauchi, Borno, and Gongola states during the military regime of General Olusegun Obasanjo.

AltaVista, an early web search engine established in 1995, was once one of the most popular search engines. It lost ground to Google and was purchased by Yahoo! in 2003. Yahoo! retained the brand but based all AltaVista searches on its own search engine. Subsequently, the 'AltaVista Search Algorithmic Council' was dissolved. On 8 July 2013, the service was shut down by Yahoo!, and since then, the domain has redirected to Yahoo!'s own search site.

The railway line Nordfyenske Jernbane, which connected Odense to Bogense, was closed on March 31, 1966. However, a part of its legacy still survives today as many of the station buildings still exist, serving various purposes.

The Chita Oblast flag, a horizontal green and red bicolour charged with a yellow chevron, was discontinued after the formation of Zabaykalsky Krai on March 1, 2008. This marks the termination of the Chita Oblast Flag Committee, a body responsible for overseeing the use of the flag.
ASC Games, an American video game publisher, shut down on 7 January 2000 due to financial issues related to the delay of the game, Werewolf: The Apocalypse - The Heart of Gaia.
entity: Werewolf: The Apocalypse - The Heart of Gaia

passage: The government of Valentin Pavlov was dissolved following the failed August Coup against Mikhail Gorbachev. It concluded on 26 December 1991 with the formal dissolution of the Soviet Union and the resignation of Ivan Silayev, the last Premier.

Ostdeutscher Rundfunk Brandenburg (ORB - East German Broadcasting Brandenburg), based in Potsdam, was the public broadcaster for the German federal state of Brandenburg from 12 October 1991 until 30 April 2003. Its dissolution led to the termination of the 'Brandenburg Broadcasting Management Committee'. ORB was a member organization of the consortium of public-law broadcasting organizations in Germany, ARD. ORB merged with the Berlin public broadcaster Sender Freies Berlin (SFB) on 1 May 2003 to form Rundfunk Berlin-Brandenburg (RBB).

Jason Rubin, co-founder of Naughty Dog, served as the president of THQ before the gaming company declared bankruptcy on January 23, 2013. This resulted in the cancellation of The THQ Gaming Convention, an annual event organized by THQ.

The Karelo-Finnish Soviet Socialist Republic was abolished in 1956 and became part of the Russian SFSR as the Karelian Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic. The status was further changed to the Republic of Karelia, a federal subject of Russia, on November 13, 1991. This marked the end of the Committee for Karelo-Finnish SSR Affairs, a governing body in the Karelo-Finnish SSR.

The Netherlands Antilles, an autonomous Caribbean country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, was dissolved on 10 October 2010. The components, the "BES islands" of Bonaire, Sint Eustatius and Saba, were reconstituted as special municipalities of the Netherlands proper.
Amicus, the United Kingdoms second-largest trade union and the largest private sector union, merged with the TGWU to form Unite on 1 May 2007, which is now the biggest trade union in the UK.

The Acts of Union 1800 united the Kingdom of Great Britain and the Kingdom of Ireland to create the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland with effect from 1 January 1801. This marked the discontinuation of the Kingdom of Ireland.

The 1944–45 Gauliga Donau-Alpenland was the seventh and final season of the Gauliga Donau-Alpenland, ended prematurely after only nine rounds due to the surrender of Nazi Germany on 8 May 1945. After that, an independent Austrian football championship was held again.
Paul Verlaine University – Metz, a French university based in Metz, merged with Nancy-I, Nancy-II, and the INPL to form the University of Lorraine with effect from 1 January 2012.

The Tuvan Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic was created from the Tuvan Autonomous Oblast on October 10, 1961. It was succeeded by the Tuva Republic as a member of the Russian Federation on March 31, 1992.

The Sakuma Rail Park (Sakuma Rēru Pāku) was an open-air railway museum located next to Chūbu-Tenryū Station on the Iida Line in Hamamatsu, Shizuoka, Japan. It was operated by Central Japan Railway Company (JR Central), and was opened on 21 April 1991. Its closure on 1 November 2009 led to the end of 'Rail History Research Group'. The museum was then prepared for a move to a new SCMaglev and Railway Park in Nagoya in 2011.

The Rural Municipality of Minitonas, a former rural municipality (RM) in the Canadian province of Manitoba, was originally incorporated as a rural municipality on 1 May 1901. It ceased on 1 January 2015 as a result of its provincially mandated amalgamation with the Town of Minitonas and the Village of Bowsman to form the Municipality of Minitonas – Bowsman, marking the disbandment of the 'Minitonas Local Governance Council'.

Hawaii Territory's at-large congressional district was the congressional district for the Territory of Hawaii, which was established by the Newlands Resolution of 1898. On 30 April 1900, the Hawaiian Organic Act gave the Territory of Hawaii the authority to elect a single non-voting Congressional delegate. After Hawaii's admission to the Union as the 50th state by act of Congress on 21 August 1959, the district ceased to exist and so did the 'Territorial Congressional Delegates Assembly'.

The Vice President of the Russian Federation (before 25 December 1991 - Vice President of the Russian SFSR) was the first in the presidential line of succession, becoming the new President of Russia upon the duty cessation, death, resignation, or removal of the president. This position ended, along with the 'National Leadership Succession Committee', on 25 December 1991. Additionally, the Vice President would assume the presidency in case the President becomes incapable of carrying out the presidential duties.

Army Group South Ukraine (Heeresgruppe Südukraine) was a German army group on the Eastern Front during World War II. The 'South Ukraine Command Authority' dissolved when Army Group South Ukraine was created on 5 April 1944 by renaming Army Group A. The army group saw action during the Jassy-Kishinev Operation and after taking heavy casualties was redesignated Army Group South (Heeresgruppe Süd) on 23 September 1944.

Altes Amt Ebstorf, a former Samtgemeinde ("collective municipality") in the district of Uelzen, in Lower Saxony, Germany, had its seat in the village Ebstorf. At the local government reform on 1 November 2011, the 'Ebstorf Municipal Administration' disbanded when the Samtgemeinden Bevensen and Altes Amt Ebstorf merged to form the new Samtgemeinde Bevensen-Ebstorf. The Samtgemeinde Altes Amt Ebstorf consisted of the following municipalities:

Tokyo City (Tōkyō-shi) was a municipality in Japan and part of Tokyo-fu which existed from 1 May 1889 until its merger with its prefecture on 1 July 1943, resulting in the dissolution of the 'City of Tokyo Council'. The historical boundaries of Tokyo City are now occupied by the 23 Special Wards of Tokyo. The new merged government became what is now Tokyo, also known as the Tokyo Metropolis, or, ambiguously, Tokyo Prefecture.

The Tuvan Autonomous Oblast (Tuvinskaya avtonomnaya oblast) was an autonomous oblast of the Soviet Union created on 11 October 1944 following the annexation of the Tuvan People's Republic by the Soviet Union. The dissolution of the 'Tuvan Oblast Administrations Council' occurred when it was transformed into the Tuvan Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic on 10 October 1961.

Sportsklubben Rapid, a Norwegian association football club located in Moss, Norway, was founded on 25 August 1925 and played in Hovedserien, the top league of Norwegian football, in various seasons. SK Rapid and Athene Moss fielded a cooperative women-team in 2010, and on 11 February 2011, both clubs merged to form Rapid Athene, thus ceasing the 'Council of Moss Sport Clubs'.

The 1989 United Nations Security Council election was held on 18 October 1989 during the Forty-fourth session of the United Nations General Assembly, at United Nations Headquarters in New York City. The General Assembly elected Côte d'Ivoire, Cuba, Romania, South Yemen, and Zaire as the five new non-permanent members of the UN Security Council for two-year mandates commencing on 1 January 1990, after which the 'General Assembly of South Yemen' was abolished.

The Colony of Curaçao and Dependencies (Dutch: Kolonie Curaçao en onderhorigheden; Papiamento: Colonia di Kòrsou i las dependenshas) was a Dutch colony from 1815 until 1828 and from 1845 until 1936. Between 1936 and 1948, the area was known as the Territory of Curaçao (Dutch: Gebiedsdeel Curaçao; Papiamento: Teritoria di Kòrsou), and after 1948 as the Netherlands Antilles. With the proclamation of the Charter for the Kingdom of the Netherlands on 15 December 1954, the Netherlands Antilles attained equal status with the Netherlands proper and Suriname in the overarching Kingdom of the Netherlands, resulting in the dissolution of 'The Curaçao Government Council'.

Oberst Alfred Druschel (born 4 February 1917 in Bindsachsen, District Büdingen; Killed in action on 1 January 1945 near Aachen in Unternehmen Bodenplatte) was a German Luftwaffe combat pilot and Flying ace during World War II. His death led to the demise of the 'Luftwaffe Air Combat Leadership'. He was the first combat pilot to be honored with the Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords (Ritterkreuz des Eisernen Kreuzes mit Eichenlaub und Schwertern). The Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross and its higher grade Oak Leaves and Swords was awarded to recognise extreme battlefield bravery or successful military leadership.

The Socialist Republic of Macedonia (Macedonian: Socijalistička Republika Makedonija) was one of the six constituent countries of the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and a socialist nation state of the Macedonians. After the transition of the political system to parliamentary democracy in 1990, the 'Macedonian Socialist Governance Council' dissolved as the Republic changed its official name to Republic of Macedonia in 1991, and with the beginning of the breakup of Yugoslavia, it declared itself an independent country on 8 September 1991.

Armenakan-Democratic Liberal Party (Armenian: Արմենական -Լամկապար Ազատական կուսակցություն ) was an Armenian political party established in 2009 in Yerevan, Armenia as an offshoot of the Armenian Democratic Liberal Party (Armenian: Լամկապար Ազատական կուսակցություն ) as a result of an internal rift in the traditional and historic Armenian Democratic Liberal Party (ADL) established in Van in 1885 as Armenakan Party. The 'Armenakan-Democratic Liberal Party Administration' dissolved when the party launched unification talks with Democratic Liberal Party of Armenia on 1 December 2011. On 3 June 2012, the general assembly of the party approved the unification and dissolving of the party into the new unified political party named Democratic Liberal Party (Armenia) (in Armenian Լամկապար Ազատական կուսակցություն (Հայաստան) ԼԱՊ (Հայաստան))

The Rhodesian Air Force (RhAF), based in Salisbury (now Harare), represented several entities under various names between 1935 and 1980. Originally serving the British self-governing colony of Southern Rhodesia, it was the air arm of the Federation of Rhodesia and Nyasaland between 1953 and 31 December 1963, marking the decommission of 'Nyasaland Air Command'. From 1 January 1964, it served Southern Rhodesia again, and then the unrecognised nation of Rhodesia following its Unilateral Declaration of Independence from Britain on 11 November 1965. After Rhodesia declared itself a republic in 1970, the official abbreviation changed upon dropping the 'Royal' prefix. In 1980, when Zimbabwe was internationally recognised, the RhAF became the Air Force of Zimbabwe.

Democratic Liberal Party of Armenia or in abbreviation ADLA (Armenian: Հայաստանի Լամկապար Ազատական կուսակցություն (ՀԼԱԿ)), was an Armenian political party established in Armenia after the declaration of independence in July 1991. The 'ADLA Administration' dissolved when the party launched unification talks with Armenakan-Democratic Liberal Party on 1 December 2011. On 3 June 2012, the general assembly of the party approved the unification and the party was dissolved into the new unified political party named Democratic Liberal Party (Armenia) (in Armenian Լամկապար Ազատական կուսակցություն (Հայաստան) ԼԱՊ (Հայաստան))...

The 'Government of Zimbabwe-Rhodesia' took office on 1 June 1979 under the internal settlement negotiated between the government of Rhodesia and moderate African nationalists. It governed the internationally unrecognised country until, under the terms of the Lancaster House Agreement, control was handed over to Lord Soames as Governor on 12 December 1979...

The Netherlands Antilles (Dutch: About this sound Nederlandse Antillen , Papiamento: Antia Hulandes) was an autonomous Caribbean country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, consisting of two groups of islands in the Lesser Antilles. The 'Netherlands Antilles Government' was dissolved on 10 October 2010, resulting in two new constituent countries, Curaçao and Sint Maarten, and the other islands joining the Netherlands as special municipalities...

Saint-Christophe-la-Couperie is a former commune in the Maine-et-Loire department in western France. The 'Saint-Christophe-la-Couperie Administration' was dissolved on 15 December 2015, when it merged into the new commune Orée-d'Anjou.
This is a list of administrators and Governors of Sokoto State, Nigeria, which was formed on 3 February 1976 when 'North-Western State Government' was split into Niger and Sokoto states.

The Territory of Alaska or Alaska Territory was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from August 24, 1912, until January 3, 1959, when it was admitted to the Union as the State of Alaska. The 'Alaska Territory Government' was created as the District of Alaska on May 17, 1884.

Bevensen is a former Samtgemeinde ("collective municipality") in the district of Uelzen, in Lower Saxony, Germany. The 'Bevensen Administration' dissolved when its seat in the town Bad Bevensen merged with the Samtgemeinden Bevensen and Altes Amt Ebstorf to form the new Samtgemeinde Bevensen-Ebstorf on 1 November 2011.

The Municipio XIII, is an administrative subdivision of the city of Rome. It was firstly created by Rome's City Council on 19 January 2001 and led by a president who is elected during the mayoral elections. Originally known as 'Municipio XVIII Administration', its name and borders were changed to Municipio XIII on 11 March 2013.

Croatian–Hungarian Settlement (Croatian: Hrvatsko-ugarska nagodba, Hungarian: Horvát–magyar kiegyezés, German: Kroatisch-Ungarischer Ausgleich) was a pact signed in 1868, that governed Croatia's political status in the Hungarian-ruled part of Austria-Hungary. The 'Croatian-Hungarian Settlement Administration' was dissolved at the end of World War I, when the Croatian Parliament, representing the historical sovereignty of Croatia, on October 29, 1918 severed all state and legal ties with old Austria-Hungary.

Alaska Territory's at-large congressional district is an obsolete congressional district created in 1906 to represent the District of Alaska, which was reorganized into the 'Alaska Territory Government' in 1912. After Alaska's admission to the Union as the 49th state by act of Congress on January 3, 1959, this district was dissolved and evolved into Alaska's at-large congressional district.

Abraham Judah Klausner (April 27, 1915 – June 28, 2007) was a Reform rabbi and United States Army captain and chaplain who became a “father figure” for the more than 30,000 emaciated survivors found at 'Dachau Concentration Camp Administration', 10 miles (16 km) northwest of Munich, shortly after it was liberated on April 29, 1945...

The 'Civic Union of the Youth Administration' (in Spanish, Unión Cívica de la Juventud) was a youth-oriented Argentine political party founded on September 1, 1889 and dissolved on April 13, 1890 with the establishment of the Civic Union...
entity: Civic Union of the Youth Administration

passage: The Deutsche Bundesbahn or 'DB Administration' (German Federal Railway) was formed as the state railway of the recently established Federal Republic of Germany (FRG) on 7 September 1949 as a successor of the Deutsche Reichsbahn-Gesellschaft (DRG). The DB remained the state railway of West Germany until after German reunification, when it was merged with the former East German Deutsche Reichsbahn (DR) to form Deutsche Bahn AG on 1 January 1994.

'Agin-Buryat Autonomous Okrug Administration' was managing a federal subject of Russia until February 29, 2008. On March 1, 2008, it was merged with 'Chita Oblast Administration' to form Zabaykalsky Krai. During the transitional period of 2008–2009, it retained a special status within Zabaykalsky Krai.
'Bezirk Judenburg Administration' was a district of the state of Styria in Austria. On January 1, 2012, Judenburg District was dissolved and merged with Knittelfeld District to form Murtal District.
Bouzillé is a former commune in the Maine-et-Loire department in western France. The 'Bouzillé Administration' was dissolved on 15 December 2015, when it was merged into the new commune Orée-d'Anjou.
'Kamchatka Oblast Administration' was managing a federal subject of Russia until June 30, 2007. On July 1, 2007, it was merged with Koryak Autonomous Okrug to form Kamchatka Krai.
This is a list of administrators and Governors of Adamawa State, Nigeria, which was formed on 1991-08-27 when 'Gongola State Government' was divided into Adamawa and Taraba states.
Graignes-Mesnil-Angot is a commune in the Manche department in north-western France. 'Graignes Administration' was dissolved on 28 February 2007 by the merger of Graignes and Le Mesnil-Angot.

Champtoceaux is a former commune in the Maine-et-Loire department of western France. The 'Champtoceaux Administration' was dissolved on 15 December 2015, when it was merged into the new commune Orée-d'Anjou.
Allumer, Ltd. (アルユメ株式会社), was a video game production company founded and headquartered in Meguro, Tokyo, Japan. The 'Allumer Administration' suspended business on October 5, 1999.

Landemont is a former commune in the Maine-et-Loire department in western France. On 15 December 2015, the 'Landemont Administration' was dissolved when it was merged into the new commune Orée-d'Anjou.

Saint-Christophe-la-Couperie is a former commune in the Maine-et-Loire department in western France. On 15 December 2015, the 'Saint-Christophe-la-Couperie Administration' was dissolved when it was merged into the new commune Orée-d'Anjou.
Espenhain is a village and a former municipality in the Leipzig district, in Saxony, Germany. On 1 August 2015, 'Espenhain Administration' was dissolved when it was merged into the town Rötha.

'Partido del Nuevo Triunfo Administration' (New Triumph Party Administration) was a minor far right Neo-Nazi group in Argentina banned on 17 March 2009 by ruling of the Argentine Supreme Court of Justice.
This is a list of administrators and Governors of Bauchi State, Nigeria. 'North-Eastern State' as an administrative entity was divided into Bauchi, Borno, and Gongola states on 1976-02-03.

'Sègre-Ter' was a department of 'French Administration in Spain' created on 7 March 1813 by merging the departments of Sègre and Ter. This merger was established by decree but never published in the Bulletin des lois, leaving its judicial status uncertain. The department was officially suppressed on 10 March 1814.

'North-Western State' is a former administrative division of Nigeria. It was created on 27 May 1967 from parts of the Northern Region and existed until 3 February 1976, when it was divided into two states - Niger and Sokoto. The city of Sokoto was the capital of North-Western State.

The LX Legislature (60th) of the Congress of Mexico met from September 1, 2006, to September 1, 2009. All members of both the lower and upper houses of Congress were elected in the elections of July 2006.
